This week, MANA De San Diego highlights Afro- Latina journalist, television newscaster, and author Gwen Ifill for #BlackHistoryMonth. Gwen made history when she became the first Afro-Latina to host a nationally televised U.S public affair program, and further broke barriers when she became the first Afro-Latina to moderate a vice-presidential campaign. Years later, Gwen's legacy and impact have allowed her to earn recognition as one of the nation's most respected journalists, and most influential role models in the media.

Join us at the AHN Uplifted Conference in Las Vegas on April 28-29! Over the course of 2 days, we will host 12 total breakout sessions. The goal of each breakout session is to give participants the chance to learn from experts and come away with actionable learnings. On Day 1, Intellectual Property and Corporate Attorney Nick Shen of Nova Law will host a workshop on brand protection and trademarks. Nick helped protect the AHN brand at the early stages by registering the Asian Hustle Network ® and the AHN trademarks. He will present a brief introduction on the importance of Brand Protection and the role of Trademarks as it pertains to businesses at all stages. The one-hour workshop will conclude with an interactive question and answer and will end with a giveaway! Reserve your spot ASAP before we sell out! See you there. 👏

Join our friends at South Asian Network this Sunday, June 26th from 1:00 - 4:00 PM as they host a Visibility + PRIDE event at their office: 18173 Pioneer Blvd Suite I, Artesia, CA 90701. There will be a march/rally down Pioneer Blvd to promote the visibility and rights of the South Asian Queer community. For those who are interested, please meet at their office at 1:00 PM. There will be a small gathering/speech at 1:30 PM, followed by the march at 2:00 PM latest (about 1.5 miles in total). There will also be keynote speakers, art, and food! Please let SAN know at your earliest convenience if you plan to attend so they can accommodate the quantity of refreshments/food. ** It will likely be a warm day so please keep that in mind when preparing for the event. Ample water will be provided!**

✊🏾Tofu Tees x Zappos 👟 First things first, this tote is not for sale. It is an exclusive piece made for @zappos that will be gifted to attendees of their Juneteenth Event. I partnered with @zapposbaae to come up with this design and am very proud of it. Juneteenth isn’t just a random word, or a holiday, it’s a part of who we are and I feel like this tote showcases that. If you don’t know what Juneteenth is, please stop reading this and go look it up! 🔒 Here is the breakdown of the design. ‘Recognition’ of our ancestors pain, hardships and strength. ‘Restoration’ of livelihood, freedom and legacy. ‘Celebration’ of our people, our struggles, our contributions and our resilience. Thank you for this amazing opportunity Zappos! ✊🏾

January is National Slavery and Human Trafficking Month and we will be highlighting information around modern day slavery and human trafficking, including the impacts on victims and communities, all month long. Although our rural tri-county area seems removed from hubs of human trafficking such as Los Angeles, the Bay Area and Sacramento, there is still human labor trafficking and human sex trafficking occurring here in our local communities. Human trafficking relies on isolation, coercion, fear and threats. Many victims of human trafficking do not initially know that they are being trafficked. California is ranked 7th in the nation for rate of cases of human trafficking, with 3.80 cases per 100,000 residents. As the most populous state in the nation, California has the highest number of total reported cases. In 2021 there have been 1,507 reported cases of human trafficking in California, with many cases going unreported and unrecognized. If you suspect someone is the victim of human trafficking call the National Human Trafficking Resource Center 1-888-373-7888 The resource center involves law enforcement only with the consent of the victim who may have reasons why they do not feel safe or comfortable involving authorities. For more information visit: humantraffickinghotline.org/report-trafficking:=:https://humantraffickinghotline.org/report-trafficking If the situation involves a minor or someone is in immediate physical danger, call 911. Also visit https://www.dhs.gov/blue-campaign for more information and resources. If you are a survivor of sexual trafficking or significant other of a sexual trafficking victim we are here to support you in your healing journey. Our Crisis Hotline is available 24/7 530-342-7273 (collect calls accepted) #nationalslaveryandhumantraffickingpreventionmonth #stopmodernslavery #bluecampaign #stophumantrafficking #endtrafficking

After serving as the first female President of Chile and the first elected female leader in South America, @mbachelet was appointed the first executive director of the United Nations Entity for Gender Equality and the Empowerment of Women. Bachelet is a physician with an encyclopedic knowledge of military strategy, worked as the Health Minister and Defense Minister of Chile, and speaks English, German, French, and Portuguese, in addition to her native Spanish. She has broken an uncountable number of barriers. We are #BetterBecauseOfHer #WHM2022 #EmpowerWomen

We're counting down to the final application deadline of Jan 31 for the Foreign Affairs IT Fellowship! This two-year fellowship program provides up to $75,000 in academic funding for your junior and senior years, or a two-year master’s program, two summer internships (with stipends), professional development and mentorship. After you successfully complete the fellowship and the State Department requirements, you receive an appointment as a Foreign Service Information Management Specialist to begin an exciting career supporting diplomacy around the world. Submit your application by the early review deadline of Jan 10 to ensure all documents are submitted correctly. You'll get a chance to resubmit documents if needed. Visit http://www.FAITFellowship.org:=:https://www.faitfellowship.org/ to learn more! #FAITFellowship #blacksintech #blackwomenintech #diversityintech @hbcuconnect @blksintech @cahsialliance @latinasintech

⚾🎞️ We're honored to host League 42's movie screening and fundraiser on Saturday, April 9 to celebrate the 75th Anniversary of Jackie Robinson breaking Major League Baseball's color barrier. Tickets to the movie "42" are just $10 General Admission. Details >> https://bit.ly/League42:=:https://wichitaorpheum.com/events/42/ Baseball fans won't want to miss the League 42 VIP Experience! This pre-show event includes a session with Bob Kendrick, the president of the Negro Leagues Baseball Museum. The reception includes a presentation and Q&A with Kendrick. Food will be provided with a cash bar available. Admission to the screening is included in the VIP experience price. Proceeds from both the screening and VIP party benefit Wichita's local League 42 whose mission is to introduce baseball to the youth of Wichita who may not have had a chance to experience the game.

March is #WomensHistoryMonth. We want to highlight a few of the most important women in the history of #publichealth! Dr. Alice Hamilton saved countless workers’ lives as a pioneer in industrial health and safety. Beginning in the 1890s, she treated working-class immigrant patients at Hull House in Chicago. She learned about how diseases, toxic chemicals, and workplace injuries hurt poorer people the most. Dr. Hamilton fought to end these disparities. She investigated companies' safety records and pushed for stronger worker protections. She also promoted the peace movement and women’s rights. In 1919, Dr. Hamilton became the first woman on the faculty at Harvard University. Read more about her life here: https://www.nps.gov/people/dr-alice-hamilton.htm

Black women in sexual and reproductive justice: 🟧 Dr. Dorothy Lavinia Brown was the first African-American female surgeon from the South and first to serve in the Tennessee General Assembly. Throughout the 1960's, she provided safe abortions in heavily-restricted Tennessee. Deriving from her medical experience and racial identity, her career in politics was dedicated to furthering abortion and civil rights. Dr. Brown's influence on Black women in medicine, abortion, and racial equality continues to live on. 🟨 Loretta J. Ross is a pioneer in the reproductive justice movement and one of the first to coin the now-commonly used "women of color" and "reproductive justice" frameworks. She served as director for organizations such as the National Organization for Women and the National Black Women's Health Project. Ross now uses her vast experience in reproductive justice to speak and teach about human rights as well as issues such as white supremacy and "call-out culture." 🟩 Monica Simpson is the current Executive Director of SisterSong Women of Color Reproductive Justice Collective. As a queer Black Southern-native, she has organized extensively against the prison industrial complex and systemic violence against Southern Black women and the LGBTQIA+ community. She was the only woman out of the founders for the first Black Gay Pride Celebration in the Bible Belt. In 2014, Simpson was named a New Civil Rights Leader by Essence Magazine. #prochoice #prochoiceisprolife #humanrights #abortionrights #reproductiverights #reproductivehealth #reproductivejustice #stopthebans #mybodymychoice #healthcareisahumanright #equalrights #TitleX #Bansoffmybody #ProtectX #abortion #abortionbans #lgbtqrights #abortionishealthcare #bhm #blackhistorymonth

Hi everyone- yesterday, we took my daughter to the protests in my city, Louisville. We wanted her to understand and see what was going on. Why people were protesting, what it all means. I've been talking to a lot of my African American friends and I shared with her their comments word for word. I want her to understand that she shouldn't be scared to join with others to support justice and equality. That first amendment rights are there for a reason. That silence in matters of justice and conscience is death, literally and figuratively. She has people in her life who are African American, people she thinks of as uncles and aunties and friends. I need her to understand that their reality is ours, we're just on the other side because of privilege- and that means we're obligated to do something. And one of the things I'm doing is trying to raise her with her eyes open to what she has going for her as a white person and what she has to do with it. ETA: The First Amendment: Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof, or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press, or of the right of the people PEACEABLY to assemble, and to petition the government for a redress of grievances. I did not include the modifier PEACEFUL in the above, as I took for granted that folks would understand I was referring to peaceful protests and protestors. Not looting and rioting- especially by people bused in from out of state just to create chaos and distract from what is actually going on- which has nothing to do with what I was talking about or what I took my daughter to or what I would urge her to do. Emotions are running high right now. I understand that. It is for that reason that I'm adding this ETA.

Cathleen Holdsworth was a young activist involved with Disability In Action (DIA) when the proposal was written for what is now called ‘Liberty Resources.’ Cassie felt a strong need for an Independent Living movement, since most of what she knew about being disabled, she learned from other disabled people. She has been involved with ADAPT for over 30 years. Most of Cassie's work experience was at Liberty Resources. She was working at Action AIDS when Bob Michaels, then CEO of LRI, asked her to return to develop clustered living. Later, Cassie served as the Director of CIL Services and later, as the Director of National Policy. Cassie continues to support the CIL by serving on the Board of Directors. She continues to learn much of what she needs to know from the Disabled Community. “I love working with the newer Activists, as I know the future is in their hands. “

The National Gay Wedding Association has announced their inaugural, Inclusive Awareness Conference, #sharethelove, January 4-6, 2022 PALM SPRINGS, CALIFORNIA – June 1, 2021 – The National Gay Wedding Association (NGWA) has announced their inaugural Inclusive Awareness Conference, #sharethelove. The conference will take place January 4-6, 2022 in Indian Wells, California at the beautiful Hyatt Regency Indian Wells Resort & Spa. The conference will bring together like-minded wedding professionals for three days of inclusive awareness training. Join our keynote speakers, Chasten Glezman Buttigieg, Teacher, Activist, and New York Times Best Selling Author, “I Have Something to Tell You”, and Sara Cunningham, founder of Free Mom Hugs and author of, “How We Sleep at Night”. “The time is now!”, said Ric Simmons Founder & Executive Director. “The wedding industry is ready for a conference to address inclusive practices to deliver a higher level of service to LGBTQ+ couples. The support has been overwhelming and we do anticipate a complete sell-out. With only 200 in-person tickets available, and 1,000 virtual tickets, it’s important our guests walk away empowered and return to their wedding business feeling supported and educated to be a leading advocate for engaged LGBTQ+ couples. Delivering a higher expectation from all partnering vendors,” explains Ric. We have created an event that will allow for relationship building and networking. Additional tickets are available for purchase to select events. The Hyatt Regency Indian Wells Resort & Spa will host conference attendees as they kick off the 3-day event with a welcome dinner & reception. Day 1 will be hosted by Cathy O’Connell, COJ Events & NGWA President. Join Cathy with inclusive speakers, advocates, and wedding industry leaders to take a close look through the eyes of an LGBTQ+ couple. Learn how to style a photo shoot, use proper hashtags, and more in one of the afternoon breakout sessions. Day 2, join our host Vice President & A Monique Affair founder, Chanda Daniels. Join Chanda along with her panel of guests and speakers, develop the plan to grow your wedding business by increasing your inclusive business practices. The conference itinerary will take the attendees on a journey of understanding inclusiveness and inclusive business practices, focusing on one basic concept: love. Listen and learn from our panelists of leading LGBTQ+ advocates and wedding industry leaders. Please visit our website for more information. Both in-person and virtual conference attendees will receive an Inclusive Awareness Certificate of attendance issued by the National Gay Wedding Association. Scheduled to appear in no particular order: Jove Meyer Owner/Creative Director Jove Meyer Events @jovemeyer, Kirsten Palladino Editorial Director and co-founder @equallywed, Chanda Monique Eddens of A Monique Affair Executive Designer and Owner @cd_chandadaniels, Sara Cunningham Founder Free Mom Hugs @freemomhugs, Cathy O’Connell President & co-founder of COJ Events, a Destination Event Design & Planning Company @cojevents, Tara Melvin Founder & CEO National Society of Black Wedding & Event Professionals @NSBWEP, Julie Novack CEO co-founder PartySlate @partyslate, Courtney Sjoberg Hashtag Queen @SheSocial.co, Ricardo Tomas Lorraine Tomas of Dallas & NGWA Director of Chapter Development @lorrainetomasweddings, Lawrence & Michael Black Gay Weddings @blackgayweddings Jason Rhee Rheefined Company @jasonroars and Chasten Glezman Buttigieg, Teacher, Activist, and New York Times Best Selling Author, “I Have Something to Tell You” @chasten.buttigieg and more! The National Gay Wedding Association is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization that offers professional and educational resources for Professional Wedding Creatives that are invested in implementing inclusive practices for LGBTQ+ couples. In the wedding industry, we must learn the appropriate language to talk about queer couples, understand innovative and new wedding traditions, and reimagine the institution of marriage as it has existed for millennia. As advocates, we must continue to pursue equality for queer people across cultures, and acquire new resources to support and uphold these standards. For LGBTQ+ couples, we provide a network of established inclusive-minded Professional Wedding Creatives and LGBTQ+ advocates who provide invaluable experience to engaged couples. Seeking inclusive experienced wedding professionals begins with NGWA. If you would like additional information about the information contained in this press release, please contact the National Gay Wedding Association at 760-799-0809 or email us at admin@NationalGayWeddingAssociation.org.

On this day in Ohio National Guard history, May 20, 1846: Ohio Gov. Mordecai Bartley orders three infantry regiments of the Ohio Militia into service for the Mexican War. Bartley’s call read in part, “Let it not be said that when our country appeals to the courage and patriotism of the citizen soldiers of Ohio for aid that that aid was not properly rendered.” Ohio military forces were organized into five infantry regiments, 15 independent companies of infantry and one company of mounted rifleman. So many Buckeyes answered the call that five companies were supplied to the Fifth United States Infantry. In the end, there were about 7,000 officers and men in the Mexican War from Ohio, which constituted about one-eighth of the entire land forces of the United States. This 1862 photo shows Maj. Gen. Samuel R. Curtis who was the adjutant general of Ohio at the outbreak of the Mexican War. After establishing Camp Washington near Cincinnati as a general rendezvous of the Ohio Militia, Curtis resigned his post to command the 3rd Ohio Volunteer Infantry during the war. (Graphic by the Ohio National Guard Heritage Center/Image courtesy of the Library of Congress) #ohiohistory #otd #ArmyHistory READ MORE: https://www.ong.ohio.gov/history/highlights/18460520-mexican-war.html:=:https://ong.ohio.gov/history/highlights/18460520-mexican-war.html

At Republic Services, we respect the unique perspectives that our employees, like Reagan C., bring to work. “Being an Asian American Pacific Islander (AAPI), or specifically Chinese-American has given me the opportunity to see things from both cultures. It is important to understand Chinese-American or AAPI is not one single group, but it is a mixture of wonderful cultures coming together to be a part of this country, this United States of America. So much has been shaped by my parents, family, friends and my Chinese heritage, but also by my American Culture. I am very proud of my Chinese heritage but I am also proud to be an American. My favorite part about being a person of multi-culture: being able to help those that are in similar situations as I am, and it is a unifying feeling. To be able to see things from both perspectives will continue to guide my path to be a better person and guide others in need,” said Reagan, who is a recycling coordinator with Republic Services. #RepublicServices #SustainabilityinAction #apahm #AAPIHeritageMonth

We will meet on the outdoor terrace of the Lewis Family Religious Life Complex. More than 50 years of civil rights legislation and movements have not ended employment discrimination. This book reframes the discourse about the “glass ceiling” that women face with respect to workplace inequality. It explores the unspoken, societally held beliefs that underlie and engender workplace behavior and failures of the law, policy and human nature that contribute “panes” and (“pains”) to the “glass ceiling.” Register at tbam.org/kerristone:=:https://www.tbam.org/index.php?src=events&srctype=detail&refno=24122&id=24122

This month we’re celebrating our Black authors for Black History Month, starting with some of our favorite fiction and biographies! “To My Children’s Children” by Sindiwe Magona is a powerful and widely acclaimed autobiography of the author’s early years in South Africa. Here tells a candid, unself-pitying story of triumph and endurance in the face of hardships relentlessly reinforced by the apartheid system. We continue to celebrate the writing and achievements of Sefi Atta, award-winning author including the two books pictured here. “Swallow”, recently adapted for a Netflix film, is a powerful tale that looks back at Lagos in the 1980s. “The Bad Immigrant,” Sefi’s most recent novel, is a comment on the immigrant experience. In particular, this book peels away nuanced layers to expose the realities of migration from Nigeria to the USA, such as the strains of adjustment and the stifling pressure to conform without loss of identity. If you are not already aware, the Caine Prize for African Writing is the leading African Literary Award—known as the African Booker—named after the Booker Prize Founder, Michael Caine. “20 Years of The Caine Prize for African Writing” showcases the winning short stories of African writers from the past 20 years and reflect the vast range of modern African experience. Be sure to find out more about this brilliant books on our website and remember that we’re celebrating our 35th anniversary this year with a 35% discount on ALL books.
